class="type-defaults"><p><strong>10. Be a good neighbor during construction</strong>. Many TIs take place in occupied buildings. There are things you can do to be mindful of disruption in someone else’s "home” such as:</p><ul><li>Take the noise restrictions seriously and keep common areas such as access hallways clean.</li><li>Limit and plan any disruption related to shell and core systems; minimize shutdowns.</li><li>Avoid entry to adjacent tenant spaces whenever possible.</li><li>Maintain proper life safety.</li><li>Communication and kept promises go a long way when disruption is unavoidable. Everyone prefers to know about it in advance.</li></ul><p><strong>11. Bonus item: manage logistics and follow Landlord guidelines</strong>. Remember that a Landlord’s focus is on keeping their many occupants happy! Expanding on #10, plan and communicate your logistical needs to move materials, crews, and debris around their existing operations effectively. Follow prescribed access routes, and always protect elevators, stairs, and floors in common areas. Early and regular interaction with the Landlord not only helps you avoid missteps, it also provides a valuable opportunity to represent their future tenant well.</p><p>In other words, prepare, collaborate, investigate, manage, and respect those around you. Useful themes in any work, with special meaning in TIs.<br
